{"title_page": "Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019", "text_new": "{{short description|Act of the Parliament of India}}\n\n{{Distinguish|Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox legislation\n| short_title = The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019\n| legislature =\n| image =\n| imagesize = 100\n| imagealt = Emblem of India\n| long_title = An Act to provide for protection of rights of transgender persons and their welfare and for matters connected therewith and incidental thereto.\n| citation = Act No. 40 of 2019 [http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf]\n| territorial_extent = [[Republic of India]]\n| enacted_by = [[Parliament of India]]\n| date_passed = 5 August 2019\n| date_passed2 = 26 November 2019\n| date_assented = 5 December 2019\n| date_signed = 5 December 2019\n| date_commenced = 10 January 2020 [http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf]\n| bill = The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2019\n| bill_citation = Bill No. 169 of 2019\n[http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/The%20Transgender%20Persons%20%28Protection%20of%20Rights%29%20Bill%2C%202019%20Bill%20Text.pdf]\n| bill_date = 19 July 2019\n| introduced_by = Minister for Social Justice and Empowerment\n| 1st_reading = 5 August 2019\n| 2nd_reading =\n| 3rd_reading =\n| white_paper =\n| committee_report = [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/SCR-%20Transgender%20Bill.pdf   43rd Report by Standing Committee on Social Justice and Empowerment, July 2017]\n| amendments =\n| repeals =\n| related = [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender%20persons%20bill%20as%20passed%20by%20LS.pdf        The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2018]<br/>[http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender_Persons_Bill%2C_2016_1.pdf  The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2016]<br/>[[Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014|The Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014]]\n| summary =\n| keywords =\n| status = In force\n\n}}\n\nThe '''Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019''' is an [[Act (law)|act]] of the [[Parliament of India]] with the objective to provide for protection of rights of [[Transgender|transgender persons]], their welfare, and other related matters. The act was introduced in the [[Lok Sabha]], the lower house of the Parliament, on 19 July 2019 by the [[Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment|Minister of Social Justice and Empowerment]], [[Thawar Chand Gehlot]], in light of the lapse of the Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2018. The 2019 act and the immediately preceding 2018 bill, were both preceded by a 2016 version. They were met with protests and criticism by transgender persons, lawyers, and activists in India. The 2016 bill was sent to a [[Standing committee (India)|standing committee]] which submitted its report in July  2017. Following this, the Lok Sabha tabled and passed a newer version of the bill in December 2018. However, it did not incorporate many of the committee's recommendations. Although members of the opposition criticised the 2019 act and assured transgender persons of not voting in favour of it, it was passed by the Lok Sabha on 5 August 2019 and by the [[Rajya Sabha]], the upper house of the Parliament, on 26 November 2019. The [[President of India|president]] assented to it on 5 December 2019, upon which the act was notified in the ''[[Gazette of India]]''. It was brought into effect from 10 January 2020 onwards vide a notification in the ''Gazette'' on the same day.\n\nFollowing protests by the [[LGBT|queer community]] against the 2016 and 2018 bills, the 2019 act has done away with few of the severely criticised provisions of the 2018 bill, such as criminalisation of begging and the establishment of a district screening committee to process applications for issuance of transgender person certificates. However, it fails to incorporate yet other principles in line with the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] judgment in ''[[National Legal Services Authority v. Union of India]]'' (''NALSA v. UOI'') in 2014, such as the right of transgender persons to self-perceived gender identity without undergoing [[sex reassignment surgery]], and mandatory reservations in jobs and educational institutions. The act has also been criticised for the lesser punishment for crimes against transgender persons compared with punishment for crimes against [[cisgender|cisgender persons]]. On 27 January 2020, the Supreme Court issued a notice to the central government in a petition filed challenging the constitutionality of the 2019 legislation.\n\nIn January 2014, while judicial pronouncement in the ''NALSA'' petition was pending, the ministry had published an Expert Committee Report on issues relating to transgender persons, after consultations with transgender persons. [[Tiruchi Siva]], of the [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]] party, had introduced the [[Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014|Rights of Transgender Persons Bill]] in 2014, in the Rajya Sabha, which was passed by the house in 2015. The 2014 bill contains provisions progressive to those in the bills introduced in between 2016 and 2019, but has been pending in the Lok Sabha since 2015. Prior to the [[Indian general elections, 2019|2019 general elections]], parties such as the [[Indian National Congress]] and [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] had promised in their respective electoral manifestoes to, respectively, withdraw the 2018 bill \u2014 while introducing a new one consulting members of the queer community \u2014 and pass the 2014 bill.\n\n==History and background==\n[[File:Hijra and companions in Eastern Bengal.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Hijras in eastern Bengal, ''circa'' 1860]]\n{{LGBT rights}}\nIn 2014, the Supreme Court of India delivered its judgment in ''National Legal Services Authority v. Union of India'' (also known as, ''NALSA v. UOI''), in which it recognised the rights of the transgender persons in India and laid down a series of measures for securing transgender persons' rights by mandating prohibition of discrimination, recommending the creation of welfare policies and reservations for transgender persons in educational institutions and jobs.<ref name=\"th1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-recognises-transgenders-as-third-gender/article5914572.ece | title=Supreme Court recognises transgenders as third gender | date=15 April 2014 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Venkatesan, J. | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614152049/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-recognises-transgenders-as-third-gender/article5914572.ece | archive-date=14 June 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> The judgment upheld the right of a transgender person to self-perceived gender identity, guaranteed by the [[Constitution of India]], in the absence of sex reassignment surgery.<ref name=\"th2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/a-promise-falls-short/article23505892.ece | title=A promise falls short | date=12 April 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> The 2014 judicial mandate stands backed by the judgments of the Supreme Court in ''[[Justice K. S. Puttaswamy (Retd.) and Anr. vs Union Of India And Ors.|Justice K. S. Puttaswamy (Retd.) and anr. v. Union of India and ors.]]'' (2017) and ''[[Navtej Singh Johar v. Union of India]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"th3\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/the-supreme-court-trans-formed/article24949441.ece | title=The Supreme Court trans-formed | date=15 September 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> The judgment in ''NALSA v. UOI'' also noted the presence of transgender persons in India throughout its history, and made reference to the [[Hijra (South Asia)|hijra, kinnar, and jogta]] communities, spread across the country and beyond in the [[Indian subcontinent]].<ref>{{cite journal | title=National Legal Services Authority versus Union of India and others | journal=Supreme Court Cases | year=2014 | volume=5 | pages=438}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-27031180 | title=India court recognises transgender people as third gender | date=15 April 2014 | agency=BBC | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811110426/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-27031180 | archive-date=11 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile the decision in the ''NALSA'' petition was still pending, an expert committee report on issues relating to transgender persons was published in January 2014, after consultations by the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment with transgender persons in August 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-wrongs/article21339721.ece | title=Rights & wrongs \u2014 on Transgender Persons Bill | date=9 December 2017 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625123619/http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-wrongs/article21339721.ece | archive-date=25 June 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/expert-panel-wants-transgender-declared-third-gender/article5781874.ece | title=Expert panel wants transgender declared third gender | date=24 March 2014 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Dhar, Aarti | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224013224/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/expert-panel-wants-transgender-declared-third-gender/article5781874.ece | archive-date=24 December 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> In this background, Tiruchi Siva of the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam party introduced a [[private member's bill]] in the Rajya Sabha, namely the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill (No.  XLIXC-C), 2014.<ref name =\"transpvt\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rajya-sabha-passes-private-bill-on-transgenders/article7138056.ece | title=RS passes Bill on transgender rights | date=24 April 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gandhi and, Ramachandran | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510072419/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rajya-sabha-passes-private-bill-on-transgenders/article7138056.ece | archive-date=10 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe government had initially asked him to withdraw the bill citing various anomalies; however, the opposition had a majority in the house and the bill was unanimously passed by the Rajya Sabha on 24 April 2015.<ref name=\"transpvt\" /> The bill was welcomed by queer rights activists in India.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/turning-point-in-transgender-rights/article7139875.ece | title=\"Turning point in transgender rights\" | date=25 April 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Srinivasan, Meera | location=Chennai}}</ref> However, some transgender persons noted their absence in the entire process and called for their recommendations being sought for.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/activists-oppose-bill-on-transgender-rights/article7993938.ece | title=Activists oppose Bill on transgender rights | date=16 December 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=Bengaluru}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/cant-erase-hijra-culture-transgender-persons-bill-1581247-2019-08-16 | title=\"We can't erase our hijra culture\" | date=16 August 2019 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sinha, Chinki | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816153625/https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/cant-erase-hijra-culture-transgender-persons-bill-1581247-2019-08-16 | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Following the passing of the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014 in 2015, it stood to be the first private member's bill to be passed by the Rajya Sabha in the preceding thirty-six years<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Rajya-Sabha-passes-first-private-members-bill-in-36-years-on-transgenders-rights/articleshow/47039967.cms | title=Rajya Sabha passes first private member's bill in 36 years, on transgenders' rights | date=25 April 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831081935/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Rajya-Sabha-passes-first-private-members-bill-in-36-years-on-transgenders-rights/articleshow/47039967.cms | archive-date=31 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> and by the Parliament in the preceding forty-five years.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rajya-sabha-private-member-bill-transgenders-rights-250096-2015-04-24 | title=Rajya Sabha passes transgenders rights bill, first private member proposal in 46 years | date=24 April 2015 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817114840/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rajya-sabha-private-member-bill-transgenders-rights-250096-2015-04-24 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Until 2015, only sixteen private member's bills had stood passed since 1947.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Just-14-private-members-bills-passed-by-Parliament-till-date-the-last-was-in-1970/articleshow/47046338.cms | title=Just 14 private member's bill passed by Parliament till date; the last was in 1970 | date=25 April 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907004217/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Just-14-private-members-bills-passed-by-Parliament-till-date-the-last-was-in-1970/articleshow/47046338.cms | archive-date=7 September 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe 2014 bill underwent significant changes when the government drafted its own version of the bill, with omissions of provisions in the 2014 bill.<ref name = \"2015bill\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/all-you-need-to-know-about-the-transgender-persons-bill-2016/article21226710.ece | title=All you need to know about the Transgender Persons Bill, 2016 | date=30 November 2017 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Abraham, Rohan | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507193832/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/all-you-need-to-know-about-the-transgender-persons-bill-2016/article21226710.ece | archive-date=7 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> After recommendations were received from transgender persons, the bill was sent to the [[Ministry of Law and Justice (India)|Ministry of Law and Justice]].<ref name = \"2015bill\"/> It came to be known as the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2015.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bill-ensures-family-life-for-transgender-children/articleshow/50374808.cms | title=Bill ensures family life for transgender children | date=30 December 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=Ghildiyal, Subodh | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901033429/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bill-ensures-family-life-for-transgender-children/articleshow/50374808.cms | archive-date=1 September 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Later, on 26 February 2016, the bill was introduced in the Lok Sabha for debate by [[Baijayant Panda]] of the [[Biju Janata Dal]] party.<ref name=\"bjd\">{{cite news | url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/lok-sabha-takes-up-bill-to-end-transgender-discrimination-1281768 | title=Lok Sabha Takes Up Bill To End Transgender Discrimination | date=27 February 2016 | agency=NDTV | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=PTI | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817124856/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/lok-sabha-takes-up-bill-to-end-transgender-discrimination-1281768 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> He argued that the bill would help extend constitutional rights and end the discrimination against transgender persons, allowing them to live a life of dignity.<ref name=\"bjd\"/> The bill was discussed in the Lok Sabha on 29 April 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/live-today-in-parliament-april-29-2016/article8536287.ece | title=Lok Sabha discusses transgender rights | date=29 April 2016 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> Siva stated that he will not be withdrawing the 2014 bill.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/article/906587/how-parliament-came-to-have-two-bills-on-transgender-persons-rights-and-why-neither-may-pass | title=How Parliament came to have two Bills on transgender persons\u2019 rights (and why neither may pass) | date=24 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Lalwani, Vijayta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103306/https://scroll.in/article/906587/how-parliament-came-to-have-two-bills-on-transgender-persons-rights-and-why-neither-may-pass | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile the 2014 bill passed by the Rajya Sabha continues to be pending,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/rajya-sabha-member-wants-to-modify-national-anthem/article28100859.ece | title=Rajya Sabha member wants to modify National Anthem | date=21 June 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> the government tabled the Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill (No. 210), 2016, on 2 August 2016, following the constitution of the Lok Sabha, post the [[Indian general elections, 2014|2014 general elections]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/explained-why-the-citizenship-amendment-bill-is-dead-for-now-5582573/ | title=Explained: Why the Citizenship Amendment Bill is dead, for now | date=13 February 2019 | agency=Indian Express | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817130024/https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/explained-why-the-citizenship-amendment-bill-is-dead-for-now-5582573/ | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The 2016 bill had various provisions reportedly regressive to the provisions in the 2014 bill.<ref name=\"scroll\">{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/article/906205/this-is-a-black-day-activists-criticise-transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha | title=\u2018This is a black day\u2019: Activists criticise Transgender Persons Bill passed in Lok Sabha | date=19 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Lalwani, Vijayta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103231/https://scroll.in/article/906205/this-is-a-black-day-activists-criticise-transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jyotiratnam\" /> The bill was met with criticism and protests from Indian transgender persons and was referred to the standing committee, which submitted its report in July 2018.<ref name=\"jyotiratnam\" /> The Lok Sabha tabled and passed a newer version of the bill with twenty-seven amendments on 17 December 2018.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ptinews.com/news/10250267_Lok-Sabha-passes-Transgender-bill.html | title=Lok Sabha passes Transgender bill | date=17 December 2018 | agency=PRI | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092137/http://ptinews.com/news/10250267_Lok-Sabha-passes-Transgender-bill.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bittuh1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-transgender-persons-bill-misses-key-demands-of-the-community/story-0c6VV1GvYuV4xqYL06zw8N.html | title=The Transgender Persons Bill misses key demands of the community | date=15 June 2019 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kondaiah, Karthik Bittu | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817053704/https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-transgender-persons-bill-misses-key-demands-of-the-community/story-0c6VV1GvYuV4xqYL06zw8N.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was once again met with severe criticism and protests pan-India, as it overlooked the recommendations made by the standing committee and suggestions offered by transgender persons.<ref name=\"revised\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/colleges-join-hands-to-protest-against-transgender-bill-2018/article25844976.ece | title=Colleges join hands to protest against Transgender Bill 2018 | date=28 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Karangutkar, Suyash | location=Mumbai}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-revised/article25783926.ece | title=Rights, revised: on the Transgender Persons Bill, 2018 | date=20 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> However, the 2018 bill stood lapsed.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-rights-bill-to-be-reintroduced/article27474400.ece | title=Transgender rights Bill to be reintroduced | date=5 June 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the constitution of the Lok Sabha, post the 2019 general elections, the bill was reintroduced on 19 July 2019 by the Minister of Social Justice and Empowerment, [[Thawar Chand Gehlot]].<ref name=\"leaflet1\">{{cite news | url=https://theleaflet.in/transgender-bill-introduced-in-the-lok-sabha/ | title=Transgender Bill introduced in the Lok Sabha | date=24 July 2019 | agency=The Leaflet | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sirohi, Nishant | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092851/https://theleaflet.in/transgender-bill-introduced-in-the-lok-sabha/ | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Before this the bill had been approved by the [[Cabinet of India|union cabinet]] on 10 July 2019.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/cabinet-approves-transgender-bill/article28355950.ece | title=Cabinet approves transgender bill | work=The Hindu Business Line | date=10 July 2019 | agency=Press Trust of India | accessdate=18 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311161745/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/cabinet-approves-transgender-bill/article28355950.ece | archive-date=11 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was passed by a voice vote in the Lok Sabha on 5 August 2019, amidst commotion in the house following the revocation of the state of Jammu and Kashmir's special status by the Parliament on the same day.<ref name=\"passedaugust\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha/article28822000.ece | title=Transgender Persons bill passed in Lok Sabha | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=PTI | location=New Delhi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/congress-opposition-parties-protest-in-lok-sabha-seek-presence-of-prime-minister-on-kashmir-decisions/articleshow/70536012.cms | title=Congress opposition parties protest in Lok Sabha seek presence of Prime Minister on Kashmir decision | date=5 August 2019 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808023548/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/congress-opposition-parties-protest-in-lok-sabha-seek-presence-of-prime-minister-on-kashmir-decisions/articleshow/70536012.cms | archive-date=8 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was introduced in the Rajya Sabha by Thawarchand Gehlot on 20 November 2019, upon which it was passed without any amendments on 26 November 2019 following a motion to refer it to a [[Select_committee#India|select committee]] that failed by 77 noes against 55 ayes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/parliament-passes-bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders/article30087790.ece |title=Parliament passes Bill to protect rights of transgenders |work=26 November 2019 |access-date=17 April 2020 |publisher=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130183741/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/parliament-passes-bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders/article30087790.ece |archive-date=30 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name =\"jaya2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/amid-opposition-trans-community-rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-bill-112971 |title=Amid opposition from trans community, Rajya Sabha passes Transgender Persons Bill |date=26 November 2019 |work=The News Minute |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414175331/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/amid-opposition-trans-community-rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-bill-112971 |archive-date=14 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/rajya-sabha-passes-criticised-transgender-rights-bill |title=Rajya Sabha Passes Controversial Transgender Rights Bill |date=26 November 2019 |work=The Wire |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128190253/https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/rajya-sabha-passes-criticised-transgender-rights-bill |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The bill received presidential assent on 5 December 2019, following which the Ministry of Law and Justice notified it in the ''Gazette of India'' as Act No. 40 of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf |title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019 [No. 40 of 2019] |date=5 December 2019 |website=socialjustice.nic.in |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412014303/http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf |archive-date=12 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name= \"despite\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/despite-massive-protests-trans-bill-gets-president-s-assent-becomes-law-113643 |title=Despite massive protests, Trans Bill gets President\u2019s assent, becomes law |date=7 December 2019 |work=The News Minute |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304050316/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/despite-massive-protests-trans-bill-gets-president-s-assent-becomes-law-113643 |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The act came into effect from 10 January 2020 onwards vide a notification in the ''Gazette'' on the same day by the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf |title=Notification, Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment |date=10 January 2020 |website=egazette.nic.in |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111034026/http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Nath |first=Damini |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-act-comes-into-effect/article30545336.ece |title=Transgender Persons Act comes into effect |date=11 January 2020 |work=The Hindu |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229091631/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-act-comes-into-effect/article30545336.ece |archive-date=29 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Statutory provisions==\nThe 2018 bill had criminalised begging \u2014 which transgender persons in India, such as the hijras and jogtas, engage in as a ritual-custom while some rely on it for livelihood \u2014 apart from mandating applications made to the [[District magistrate (India)|district magistrate]] to be screened through a district screening committee for issuance of transgender person certificates.<ref name =\"indiatoday2017\"/><ref name=\"billreaction1\"/> The screening committee was to be composed of five people including a chief medical officer, district social welfare officer, psychologist/psychiatrist, and a representative of the transgender persons<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.prsindia.org/billtrack/transgender-persons-protection-rights-bill-2016 | title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2016 | publisher=PRS Legislative Research | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=PRS India | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819031027/http://www.prsindia.org/billtrack/transgender-persons-protection-rights-bill-2016 | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/against-the-mandate-for-inclusion/article25791080.ece | title=Against the mandate for inclusion: the Transgender Persons Bill 2018 | date=21 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=Banerjie, Ajita}}</ref> The 2018 bill had also not provided for mandatory reservations for transgender persons and mandated lower punishment for crimes against transgender persons, as compared to punishment for crimes against cisgender persons under the [[Indian Penal Code]].<ref name =\"jyotiratnam\"/><ref name=\"bittuh1\"/> It also ensured a family-life for transgender children, by prohibiting their separation from their family, without taking into account harassment and discrimination they may face within their family as a result of which they may choose to be separated and reside with transgender persons.<ref name = \"herald\"/><ref name = \"economic\"/> A transgender child, as per the provisions, could be separated from their family only by a court order.<ref name = \"revised\"/> The 2018 bill provided for undergoing sex reassignment surgery as a mandatory pre-requirement to be identified as male or female.<ref name =\"frontline\">{{Cite news |url=https://frontline.thehindu.com/dispatches/article25957990.ece |title=Stiff opposition to transgender persons Bill |last=Venkatesan |first=V. |date=10 January 2019 |work=Frontline |access-date=20 September 2019 |last2=Kaur |first2=Tanveer}}</ref> The 2019 act does away only with few of the criticised provisions of the 2018 bill, such as the district screening committee and the criminalisation of begging.<ref name=\"reuters1\"/>\n\nThe statutory provisions of the 2019 act prohibit discrimination against transgender persons.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-lgbt-lawmaking/india-introduces-new-trans-rights-bill-in-parliament-after-backlash-idUSKCN1UE28S | title=India introduces new trans rights bill in parliament after backlash | date=19 July 2019 | agency=Reuters | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Banerji, Annie | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074604/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-lgbt-lawmaking/india-introduces-new-trans-rights-bill-in-parliament-after-backlash-idUSKCN1UE28S | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Similar to the 2018 bill, the 2019 act includes [[intersex|intersex persons]], hijras, jogtas, and [[kinnar]]s within its definition of transgender persons,<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/govt-making-rules-for-us-without-us-transgenders/article29104679.ece | title=Govt. making rules for us without us: transgenders | date=16 August 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Aggarwal, Aarushi | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815231759/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/govt-making-rules-for-us-without-us-transgenders/article29104679.ece | archive-date=15 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> though it does not define terms such as trans-man, trans-woman, and [[genderqueer]].<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref name=\"tribune1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/comment/bringing-transgenders-into-mainstream/807918.html |title=Bringing transgenders into mainstream |last=Quraishi |first=S. Y. |date=26 July 2019 |work=The Tribune |accessdate=17 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817104013/https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/comment/bringing-transgenders-into-mainstream/807918.html |archive-date=17 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Both, the 2019 act as well as the 2018 bill, describe a transgender person as someone whose gender does not match with the gender assigned to them at birth.<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/The%20Transgender%20Persons%20%28Protection%20of%20Rights%29%20Bill%2C%202019%20Bill%20Text.pdf |title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill (No. 169), 2019 |work=PRS Legislative Research |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nUnder the provisions of the 2019 act, a transgender person can apply to the district magistrate for a transgender person certificate which will give them the right to change the name on their birth certificate and have all documents updated accordingly.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-rights-bill-a-stunted-understanding-of-gender-and-equality | title=Transgender Rights Bill: A Stunted Understanding of Gender and Equality | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The Wire | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gandhi, and Ghia | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802165656/https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-rights-bill-a-stunted-understanding-of-gender-and-equality | archive-date=2 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> However, similar to the 2018 bill provisions, a transgender person can be identified as male or female only after applying for a revised certificate to the district magistrate, post sex reassignment surgery.<ref name=\"newsminute1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-transgender-persons-bill-2018-public-health-nightmare-community-94206 | title=Why Transgender Persons Bill 2018 is a healthcare nightmare for the community | date=30 December 2018 | agency=The News Minute | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Karpagam, Sylvia | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074604/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-transgender-persons-bill-2018-public-health-nightmare-community-94206 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 act also protects transgender children and provides for states and institutions to come up with adequate policies for the welfare of transgender persons.<ref name=\"dh\">{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders-passed-in-ls-752193.html | title=Bill to protect rights of transgenders passed in LS | date=5 August 2019 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kumar, Prakash | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817095008/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders-passed-in-ls-752193.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name = \"economic\">{{cite news | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/transgender-rights-bill-introduced-in-lok-sabha-may-be-taken-up-next-week/articleshow/70301454.cms | title=Transgender Rights Bill introduced in Lok Sabha, may be taken up next week | date=20 July 2019 | agency=Economic Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sharma, Nidhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817094010/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/transgender-rights-bill-introduced-in-lok-sabha-may-be-taken-up-next-week/articleshow/70301454.cms | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Similar to the provisions of the 2018 bill, under the provisions of the 2019 act a transgender child can be separated from their family by a court order.<ref name = \"revised\"/> However, unlike the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014 neither the 2018 bill nor the 2019 act provide for mandatory reservations for transgender persons in educational institutions and jobs.<ref name=\"leaflet1\"/> The 2014 bill had provided for two per-cent reservations in educational institutions and public employment.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/a-law-that-defeats-its-purpose/article25854190.ece | title=A law that defeats its purpose | date=29 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> Similar to the 2018 bill, the 2019 act provides for punishment for crimes against transgender persons, which stands as an imprisonment for a term not less than six months but which may extend to two years and a fine.<ref name =\"jyotiratnam\"/><ref name =\"tribune1\"/> The 2019 act, as well as the 2018 bill, also provide for the constitution of a National Council for Transgender Persons.<ref name = \"passedaugust\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-lok-sabha-passes-bill-to-prohibit-discrimination-against-transgenders-2779179 | title=Lok Sabha passes bill to prohibit discrimination against transgenders | date=5 August 2019 | agency=DNA | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=ANI | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806145618/https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-lok-sabha-passes-bill-to-prohibit-discrimination-against-transgenders-2779179 | archive-date=6 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and reactions==\n[[File:Protest against Transgender Bill in Mumbai, India.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Protests against the 2018 bill in [[Mumbai]], in December 2018]]\nThe 2018 bill passed by the Lok Sabha was widely criticised by transgender persons, activists, students, and lawyers.<ref name=\"gautamh1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-rajya-sabha-must-amend-the-transgender-persons-bill/story-WEyPFztPVABpfaQyDYBt5I.html | title=The Rajya Sabha must amend the Transgender Persons Bill | date=5 January 2019 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Bhatia, Gautam | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817073521/https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-rajya-sabha-must-amend-the-transgender-persons-bill/story-WEyPFztPVABpfaQyDYBt5I.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Transgender persons protested in various cities in India calling the provisions regressive and in violation of the Supreme Court judgment in 2014.<ref name=\"bittuh1\"/><ref name=\"jyotiratnam\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/transgender-bill-criminalises-community-say-activists-seek-its-overhaul/story-U6hfkKpilq6bxsDAd2WvJI.html | title=Transgender bill criminalises community, say activists; seek its overhaul | date=19 December 2018 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Jyoti, and Ratnam | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817072656/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/transgender-bill-criminalises-community-say-activists-seek-its-overhaul/story-U6hfkKpilq6bxsDAd2WvJI.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The criminalisation of begging under the 2018 bill was to affect transgender persons in India, such as hijras and jogtas, who engage in begging as a ritual-custom while some rely on it for livelihood.<ref name =\"indiatoday2017\">{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lgbtq-community-protests-against-transgender-persons-bill-1110328-2017-12-17 | title=LGBTQ community protests against Transgender Persons Bill | date=17 December 2017 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Hasan, Ilma | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092306/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lgbtq-community-protests-against-transgender-persons-bill-1110328-2017-12-17 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"billreaction1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/trans-activists-up-the-ante-to-challenge-bill/article25945066.ece | title=Trans activists up the ante, to challenge Bill | date=9 January 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Ravi, Sidharth | location=New Delhi}}</ref> It was alleged by critics that the provision of the district screening committee left gaps for incompetence and prejudice.<ref name =\"herald\">{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/opinion/second-edit/transgender-bill-remove-709703.html | title=Transgender Bill: remove drawbacks | date=24 December 2018 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030729/https://www.deccanherald.com/opinion/second-edit/transgender-bill-remove-709703.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' reported that even if the provision of a district screening committee existed to prevent imposters from seeking benefits of government welfare schemes, such an arrangement cannot be made at the expense of transgender persons' right to self-determination.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/editorials/transgender-rights-should-not-depend-on-a-screening/story-c1oqqLOTEzSAfyBoV0fWWN.html | title=Transgender rights should not depend on a screening | date=19 February 2018 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030729/https://www.hindustantimes.com/editorials/transgender-rights-should-not-depend-on-a-screening/story-c1oqqLOTEzSAfyBoV0fWWN.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The definition of transgender persons under the 2018 bill, retained by the 2019 act, was reported by ''[[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]]'' to be at variance with international expert understanding of the term.<ref name =\"frontline\"/>\n\nThe 2018 bill and 2019 act have been met with protests by transgender persons.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/dec/22/1k-trans-people-from-pondy-tn-protest-against-new-law-1914889.html | title=Over 1,000 transgenders from Pondicherry, Tamil Nadu protest against new law | date=22 December 2018 | agency=New Indian Express | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030732/http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/dec/22/1k-trans-people-from-pondy-tn-protest-against-new-law-1914889.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Their passing by the parliament has been referred to some transgender persons as \"black day\" and \"gender justice murder day\".<ref name= \"despite\"/><ref name = \"scroll\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/aug/08/transgender-persons-bill-evokes-mixed-responses-2015785.html | title=Transgender Persons Bill evokes mixed responses | date=8 August 2019 | agency=The New Indian Express | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gowda, Varsha | location=Bengaluru | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103657/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/aug/08/transgender-persons-bill-evokes-mixed-responses-2015785.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Yet others described them as \"draconian and discriminatory\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/bill-will-deprive-us-of-right-to-live-with-dignity-say-transgender-activists/article25837198.ece |title=Bill will deprive us of right to live with dignity, say transgender activists |last=Karangutkar |first=Suyash |date=27 December 2018 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref> After the 2018 bill was passed by the Lok Sabha in December 2018, members of the opposition in Rajya Sabha had stated they will not let the bill pass in its present form in Rajya Sabha.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/latest/907430/transgender-persons-bill-opposition-mps-in-rajya-sabha-promise-not-to-pass-draft-law | title=Transgender Persons Bill: Opposition MPs in Rajya Sabha promise not to pass draft law | date=28 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103316/https://scroll.in/latest/907430/transgender-persons-bill-opposition-mps-in-rajya-sabha-promise-not-to-pass-draft-law | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Protestors alleged the 2018 bill to be institutionalising violence and claimed neglect of recommendations made by the standing committee and transgender persons.<ref name=\"hubbali\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/withdraw-transgenders-bill-table-it-again-with-changes/article25875808.ece |title=\u2018Withdraw Transgenders Bill, table it again with changes\u2019  |date=1 January 2019 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref> Transgender persons called for applications to the district magistrate for issuance of transgender certificates, lesser punishment for crimes against transgender persons, and absence of provisions on mandatory reservations for transgender persons regressive to the judicial mandate of the Supreme Court in 2014 in ''NALSA v. UOI'', thereby violating right to equality and other fundamental rights of transgender persons.<ref name=\"hubbali\"/><ref name=\"newsminute2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/trans-bill-2019-passed-lok-sabha-why-trans-community-india-rejecting-it-106695 | title=Trans Bill 2019 passed in Lok Sabha: Why the trans community in India is rejecting it | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The News Minute | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Dharmadhikari, Sanyukta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074728/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/trans-bill-2019-passed-lok-sabha-why-trans-community-india-rejecting-it-106695 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nIn the run-up to the 2019 general elections to the Lok Sabha, Indian National Congress had promised in its electoral manifesto to withdraw the 2018 bill and introduce a new one, in consultation with members of the queer community.<ref name = \"manifesto\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestatesman.com/elections-2019/congress-releases-poll-manifesto-promises-jobs-benefits-farmers-niti-aayog-1502742568.html | title=Congress manifesto promises 34 lakh jobs, farmer welfare, says will scrap NITI Aayog | date=2 April 2019 | agency=The Statesman | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=SNS Web | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817134723/https://www.thestatesman.com/elections-2019/congress-releases-poll-manifesto-promises-jobs-benefits-farmers-niti-aayog-1502742568.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The Communist Party of India (Marxist) had supported the passing of the 2014 bill in its electoral manifesto.<ref name = \"manifesto\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/elections/lok-sabha-2019/the-invisible-third-gender-voters/article26764806.ece | title=The invisible \u2018third gender\u2019 voters | date=8 April 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Rosario, Kennith | location=Mumbai}}</ref> In April 2019, transgender rights activist, [[Laxmi Narayan Tripathi]], met the then [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] National General Secretary, [[Ram Madhav]], seeking that the party would introduce a revised bill if it comes back to power.<ref name=\"laxmi\">{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/transgender-activist-meets-ram-madhav-seeks-revised-bill-if-bjp-is-returned-to-power/articleshow/68745108.cms | title=Transgender activist meets Ram Madhav, seeks revised bill if BJP is returned to power | work=Times of India | date=5 April 2019 | accessdate=18 April 2020 | author=Pandit, Ambika | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920204451/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/transgender-activist-meets-ram-madhav-seeks-revised-bill-if-bjp-is-returned-to-power/articleshow/68745108.cms | archive-date=20 September 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Madhav ensured that the bill would address the concerns of the transgender community.<ref name=\"laxmi\"/> Soon after news reported that the 2019 bill was approved by the union cabinet, transgender rights activists called for a press conference in Delhi to address the issue.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-bill-cabinet-lok-sabha-activists | title=Trans Activists Demand Release of Full Text of Cabinet-Approved Transgender Bill | work=The Wire | date=17 July 2019 | accessdate=18 April 2020 | author=Sharma, Raghavi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817091259/https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-bill-cabinet-lok-sabha-activists | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> On 24 November 2019, two days before the bill was passed by the parliament, protests were staged by the queer community in New Delhi and [[Bengaluru]] as part of the [[Delhi Queer Pride Parade|Delhi queer pride parade]] and the [[Bengaluru Namma Pride March]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/namma-pride-march-rainbow-spreads-cheer-but-with-a-dash-of-black/articleshow/72216384.cms | title=Namma Pride March: Rainbow spread cheer, but with a dash of black | date=25 November 2019 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Iyer, Swathy R | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129065826/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/namma-pride-march-rainbow-spreads-cheer-but-with-a-dash-of-black/articleshow/72216384.cms | archive-date=29 November 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/delhi-marched-against-trans-bill-2019-on-pride-day-779641.html | title=Delhi marched against Trans Bill 2019 on Pride Day | date=25 November 2019 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Banerjee, Rohini | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123135718/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/delhi-marched-against-trans-bill-2019-on-pride-day-779641.html | archive-date=23 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jaya\">{{Cite news |last=Pathak |first=Sushmita |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/12/04/784398783/india-just-passed-a-trans-rights-bill-why-are-trans-activists-protesting-it |title=India Just Passed A Trans Rights Bill. Why Are Trans Activists Protesting It? |date=4 December 2019 |work=National Public Radio |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303211742/https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/12/04/784398783/india-just-passed-a-trans-rights-bill-why-are-trans-activists-protesting-it |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The legislation also drew criticism from the [[All India Mahila Congress]] and opposition from parliamentarians including [[Jaya Bachchan]] and [[Sasmit Patra]], while [[Derek O'Brien (politician)|Derek O\u2019Brien]] and Tiruchi Siva also expressed their concerns before the house.<ref name=\"jaya2\"/><ref name=\"jaya\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/a-bill-meant-to-protect-indias-transgender-community-instead-leaves-them-angry-and-aggrieved/2019/11/29/6c2c7b7e-116b-11ea-924c-b34d09bbc948_story.html | title=A bill meant to protect India\u2019s transgender community instead leaves them angry and aggrieved | date=30 November 2019 | agency=The Washington Post | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Masih, Niha | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302034520/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/a-bill-meant-to-protect-indias-transgender-community-instead-leaves-them-angry-and-aggrieved/2019/11/29/6c2c7b7e-116b-11ea-924c-b34d09bbc948_story.html | archive-date=2 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> After the legislation was passed by the parliament, transgender persons and activists protested against the legislation, organised meetings to address the situation, and urged the president not to sign and assent to the bill.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/other/protests-held-in-dadar-against-transgender-persons-bill-2019/articleshow/72309119.cms | title=Protests held in Dadar against Transgender Persons Bill 2019 | work=Mumbai Mirror | date=1 December 2019 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201051151/https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/other/protests-held-in-dadar-against-transgender-persons-bill-2019/articleshow/72309119.cms | archive-date=1 December 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jaya\"/> <ref>{{Cite news |last=Khan |first=Fatima |url=https://theprint.in/india/murder-of-gender-justice-activists-urge-president-kovind-not-to-sign-transgender-bill/327360/ |title=\u2018Murder of gender justice\u2019 \u2014 activists urge President Kovind not to sign transgender bill |date=27 November 2019 |work=The Print |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201121026/https://theprint.in/india/murder-of-gender-justice-activists-urge-president-kovind-not-to-sign-transgender-bill/327360/ |archive-date=1 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> There were also protests by the queer community against the act as part of the [[Queer Azaadi Mumbai|Mumbai pride parade]], in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/take-back-trans-act-mumbai-trans-community/1726557 | title=Take back Trans Act: Mumbai Trans community | work=Outlook | date=5 February 2020 | agency=IANS | accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/mumbai-pride-2020-thousands-stand-in-solidarity-with-queer-muslims-amid-caa-nrc-chaos-urge-govt-to-amend-draconian-transgender-act-7991111.html | title=Mumbai Pride 2020: Thousands stand in solidarity with queer Muslims amid CAA-NRC chaos, urge govt to amend 'draconian' Transgender Act | work=Firstpost | date=25 February 2020 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Manral, Avnisha | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315122340/https://www.firstpost.com/india/mumbai-pride-2020-thousands-stand-in-solidarity-with-queer-muslims-amid-caa-nrc-chaos-urge-govt-to-amend-draconian-transgender-act-7991111.html | archive-date=15 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe legislation has been criticised by [[Human Rights Watch]] and the [[International Commission of Jurists]].<ref name=\"jurists\">{{Cite news |last=Sharma |first=Neetu Chandra |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-protection-of-rights-bill-2019-11574774522034.html |title=Rajya Sabha passes Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2019 |date=26 November 2019 |work=Live Mint |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128004011/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-protection-of-rights-bill-2019-11574774522034.html |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"hrw\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/07/23/india-transgender-bill-raises-rights-concerns | title=India: Transgender Bill Raises Rights Concerns | date=23 July 2019 | agency=Human Rights Watch | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New York | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730050854/https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/07/23/india-transgender-bill-raises-rights-concerns | archive-date=30 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> On 27 January 2020, the Supreme Court issued a notice to the central government in a petition filed by advocate and transgender rights activist, Swati Bidhan Baruah, challenging the constitutionality of the 2019 legislation.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act/story-HfBrPZBTFmusm9theecWoL.html | title=Supreme Court notice to Centre on plea against transgender act | work=Hindustan Times | date=28 January 2020 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129045020/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act/story-HfBrPZBTFmusm9theecWoL.html | archive-date=29 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act-2019-798774.html | title=Supreme Court notice to Centre on plea against Transgender Act, 2019| work=Deccan Herald | date=27 January 2020 | agency=Tripathi, Ashish | accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[LGBT rights in India]]\n*[[Human rights in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019}}\n* [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Expert_Committee_Report_%282014%29_1.pdf   Report of the Expert Committee on Issues Relating to Transgender Persons (27 January 2014)]\n* [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender_Bill%2C_2015_-_PMB_passed_in_RS_2.pdf   The Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014]\n\n{{Indian legislation}}\n{{LGBT in India}}\n{{Transgender topics}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT rights in India]]\n[[Category:Modi administration]]\n[[Category:Transgender law]]\n[[Category:2019 in Indian law]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Act of the Parliament of India}}\n\n{{Distinguish|Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox legislation\n| short_title = The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019\n| legislature =\n| image =\n| imagesize = 100\n| imagealt = Emblem of India\n| long_title = An Act to provide for protection of rights of transgender persons and their welfare and for matters connected therewith and incidental thereto.\n| citation = Act No. 40 of 2019 [http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf]\n| territorial_extent = [[Republic of India]]\n| enacted_by = [[Parliament of India]]\n| date_passed = 5 August 2019\n| date_passed2 = 26 November 2019\n| date_assented = 5 December 2019\n| date_signed = 5 December 2019\n| date_commenced = 10 January 2020 [http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf]\n| bill = The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2019\n| bill_citation = Bill No. 169 of 2019\n[http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/The%20Transgender%20Persons%20%28Protection%20of%20Rights%29%20Bill%2C%202019%20Bill%20Text.pdf]\n| bill_date = 19 July 2019\n| introduced_by = Minister for Social Justice and Empowerment\n| 1st_reading = 5 August 2019\n| 2nd_reading =\n| 3rd_reading =\n| white_paper =\n| committee_report = [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/SCR-%20Transgender%20Bill.pdf   43rd Report by Standing Committee on Social Justice and Empowerment, July 2017]\n| amendments =\n| repeals =\n| related = [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender%20persons%20bill%20as%20passed%20by%20LS.pdf        The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2018]<br/>[http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender_Persons_Bill%2C_2016_1.pdf  The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2016]<br/>[[Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014|The Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014]]\n| summary =\n| keywords =\n| status = In force\n\n}}\n\nThe '''Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019''' is an [[Act (law)|act]] of the [[Parliament of India]] with the objective to provide for protection of rights of [[Transgender|transgender persons]], their welfare, and other related matters. The act was introduced in the [[Lok Sabha]], the lower house of the Parliament, on 19 July 2019 by the [[Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment|Minister of Social Justice and Empowerment]], [[Thawar Chand Gehlot]], in light of the lapse of the Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2018. The 2019 act and the immediately preceding 2018 bill, were both preceded by a 2016 version,. They were met with protests and criticism by transgender persons, lawyers, and activists in India. The 2016 bill was sent to a [[Standing committee (India)|standing committee]] which submitted its report in July  2017. Following this, the Lok Sabha tabled and passed a newer version of the bill in December 2018. However, it did not incorporate many of the committee's recommendations. Although members of the opposition criticised the 2019 act and assured transgender persons of not voting in favour of it, it was passed by the Lok Sabha on 5 August 2019 and by the [[Rajya Sabha]], the upper house of the Parliament, on 26 November 2019. The [[President of India|president]] assented to it on 5 December 2019, upon which the act was notified in the ''[[Gazette of India]]''. It was brought into effect from 10 January 2020 onwards vide a notification in the ''Gazette'' on the same day.\n\nFollowing protests by the [[LGBT|queer community]] against the 2016 and 2018 bills, the 2019 act has done away with few of the severely criticised provisions of the 2018 bill, such as criminalisation of begging and the establishment of a district screening committee to process applications for issuance of transgender person certificates. However, it fails to incorporate yet other principles in line with the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] judgment in ''[[National Legal Services Authority v. Union of India]]'' (''NALSA v. UOI'') in 2014, such as the right of transgender persons to self-perceived gender identity without undergoing [[sex reassignment surgery]], and mandatory reservations in jobs and educational institutions. The act has also been criticised for the lesser punishment for crimes against transgender persons compared with punishment for crimes against [[cisgender|cisgender persons]]. On 27 January 2020, the Supreme Court issued a notice to the central government in a petition filed challenging the constitutionality of the 2019 legislation\n\nIn January 2014, while judicial pronouncement in the ''NALSA'' petition was pending, the ministry had published an Expert Committee Report on issues relating to transgender persons, after consultations with transgender persons. [[Tiruchi Siva]], of the [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]] party, had introduced the [[Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014|Rights of Transgender Persons Bill]] in 2014, in the Rajya Sabha, which was passed by the house in 2015. The 2014 bill contains provisions progressive to those in the bills introduced in between 2016 and 2019, but has been pending in the Lok Sabha since 2015. Prior to the [[Indian general elections, 2019|2019 general elections]], parties such as the [[Indian National Congress]] and [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] had promised in their respective electoral manifestoes to, respectively, withdraw the 2018 bill \u2014 while introducing a new one consulting members of the queer community \u2014 and pass the 2014 bill.\n\n==History and background==\n[[File:Hijra and companions in Eastern Bengal.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Hijras in eastern Bengal, ''circa'' 1860]]\n{{LGBT rights}}\nIn 2014, the Supreme Court of India delivered its judgment in ''National Legal Services Authority v. Union of India'' (also known as, ''NALSA v. UOI''), in which it recognised the rights of the transgender persons in India and laid down a series of measures for securing transgender persons' rights by mandating prohibition of discrimination, recommending the creation of welfare policies and reservations for transgender persons in educational institutions and jobs.<ref name=\"th1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-recognises-transgenders-as-third-gender/article5914572.ece | title=Supreme Court recognises transgenders as third gender | date=15 April 2014 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Venkatesan, J. | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614152049/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/supreme-court-recognises-transgenders-as-third-gender/article5914572.ece | archive-date=14 June 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> The judgment upheld the right of a transgender person to self-perceived gender identity, guaranteed by the [[Constitution of India]], in the absence of sex reassignment surgery.<ref name=\"th2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/a-promise-falls-short/article23505892.ece | title=A promise falls short | date=12 April 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> The 2014 judicial mandate stands backed by the judgments of the Supreme Court in ''[[Justice K. S. Puttaswamy (Retd.) and Anr. vs Union Of India And Ors.|Justice K. S. Puttaswamy (Retd.) and anr. v. Union of India and ors.]]'' (2017) and ''[[Navtej Singh Johar v. Union of India]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"th3\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/the-supreme-court-trans-formed/article24949441.ece | title=The Supreme Court trans-formed | date=15 September 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> The judgment in ''NALSA v. UOI'' also noted the presence of transgender persons in India throughout its history, and made reference to the [[Hijra (South Asia)|hijra, kinnar, and jogta]] communities, spread across the country and beyond in the [[Indian subcontinent]].<ref>{{cite journal | title=National Legal Services Authority versus Union of India and others | journal=Supreme Court Cases | year=2014 | volume=5 | pages=438}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-27031180 | title=India court recognises transgender people as third gender | date=15 April 2014 | agency=BBC | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811110426/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-27031180 | archive-date=11 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile the decision in the ''NALSA'' petition was still pending, an expert committee report on issues relating to transgender persons was published in January 2014, after consultations by the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment with transgender persons in August 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-wrongs/article21339721.ece | title=Rights & wrongs \u2014 on Transgender Persons Bill | date=9 December 2017 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625123619/http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-wrongs/article21339721.ece | archive-date=25 June 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/expert-panel-wants-transgender-declared-third-gender/article5781874.ece | title=Expert panel wants transgender declared third gender | date=24 March 2014 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Dhar, Aarti | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224013224/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/expert-panel-wants-transgender-declared-third-gender/article5781874.ece | archive-date=24 December 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> In this background, Tiruchi Siva of the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam party introduced a [[private member's bill]] in the Rajya Sabha, namely the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill (No.  XLIXC-C), 2014.<ref name =\"transpvt\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rajya-sabha-passes-private-bill-on-transgenders/article7138056.ece | title=RS passes Bill on transgender rights | date=24 April 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gandhi and, Ramachandran | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510072419/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rajya-sabha-passes-private-bill-on-transgenders/article7138056.ece | archive-date=10 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe government had initially asked him to withdraw the bill citing various anomalies; however, the opposition had a majority in the house and the bill was unanimously passed by the Rajya Sabha on 24 April 2015.<ref name=\"transpvt\" /> The bill was welcomed by queer rights activists in India.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/turning-point-in-transgender-rights/article7139875.ece | title=\"Turning point in transgender rights\" | date=25 April 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Srinivasan, Meera | location=Chennai}}</ref> However, some transgender persons noted their absence in the entire process and called for their recommendations being sought for.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/activists-oppose-bill-on-transgender-rights/article7993938.ece | title=Activists oppose Bill on transgender rights | date=16 December 2015 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=Bengaluru}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/cant-erase-hijra-culture-transgender-persons-bill-1581247-2019-08-16 | title=\"We can't erase our hijra culture\" | date=16 August 2019 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sinha, Chinki | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816153625/https://www.indiatoday.in/india-today-insight/story/cant-erase-hijra-culture-transgender-persons-bill-1581247-2019-08-16 | archive-date=16 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Following the passing of the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014 in 2015, it stood to be the first private member's bill to be passed by the Rajya Sabha in the preceding thirty-six years<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Rajya-Sabha-passes-first-private-members-bill-in-36-years-on-transgenders-rights/articleshow/47039967.cms | title=Rajya Sabha passes first private member's bill in 36 years, on transgenders' rights | date=25 April 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831081935/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Rajya-Sabha-passes-first-private-members-bill-in-36-years-on-transgenders-rights/articleshow/47039967.cms | archive-date=31 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> and by the Parliament in the preceding forty-five years.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rajya-sabha-private-member-bill-transgenders-rights-250096-2015-04-24 | title=Rajya Sabha passes transgenders rights bill, first private member proposal in 46 years | date=24 April 2015 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817114840/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/rajya-sabha-private-member-bill-transgenders-rights-250096-2015-04-24 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Until 2015, only sixteen private member's bills had stood passed since 1947.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Just-14-private-members-bills-passed-by-Parliament-till-date-the-last-was-in-1970/articleshow/47046338.cms | title=Just 14 private member's bill passed by Parliament till date; the last was in 1970 | date=25 April 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907004217/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Just-14-private-members-bills-passed-by-Parliament-till-date-the-last-was-in-1970/articleshow/47046338.cms | archive-date=7 September 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe 2014 bill underwent significant changes when the government drafted its own version of the bill, with omissions of provisions in the 2014 bill.<ref name = \"2015bill\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/all-you-need-to-know-about-the-transgender-persons-bill-2016/article21226710.ece | title=All you need to know about the Transgender Persons Bill, 2016 | date=30 November 2017 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Abraham, Rohan | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507193832/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/all-you-need-to-know-about-the-transgender-persons-bill-2016/article21226710.ece | archive-date=7 May 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> After recommendations were received from transgender persons, the bill was sent to the [[Ministry of Law and Justice (India)|Ministry of Law and Justice]].<ref name = \"2015bill\"/> It came to be known as the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2015.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bill-ensures-family-life-for-transgender-children/articleshow/50374808.cms | title=Bill ensures family life for transgender children | date=30 December 2015 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=Ghildiyal, Subodh | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901033429/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bill-ensures-family-life-for-transgender-children/articleshow/50374808.cms | archive-date=1 September 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Later, on 26 February 2016, the bill was introduced in the Lok Sabha for debate by [[Baijayant Panda]] of the [[Biju Janata Dal]] party.<ref name=\"bjd\">{{cite news | url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/lok-sabha-takes-up-bill-to-end-transgender-discrimination-1281768 | title=Lok Sabha Takes Up Bill To End Transgender Discrimination | date=27 February 2016 | agency=NDTV | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=PTI | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817124856/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/lok-sabha-takes-up-bill-to-end-transgender-discrimination-1281768 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> He argued that the bill would help extend constitutional rights and end the discrimination against transgender persons, allowing them to live a life of dignity.<ref name=\"bjd\"/> The bill was discussed in the Lok Sabha on 29 April 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/live-today-in-parliament-april-29-2016/article8536287.ece | title=Lok Sabha discusses transgender rights | date=29 April 2016 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> Siva stated that he will not be withdrawing the 2014 bill.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/article/906587/how-parliament-came-to-have-two-bills-on-transgender-persons-rights-and-why-neither-may-pass | title=How Parliament came to have two Bills on transgender persons\u2019 rights (and why neither may pass) | date=24 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Lalwani, Vijayta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103306/https://scroll.in/article/906587/how-parliament-came-to-have-two-bills-on-transgender-persons-rights-and-why-neither-may-pass | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhile the 2014 bill passed by the Rajya Sabha continues to be pending,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/rajya-sabha-member-wants-to-modify-national-anthem/article28100859.ece | title=Rajya Sabha member wants to modify National Anthem | date=21 June 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> the government tabled the Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill (No. 210), 2016, on 2 August 2016, following the constitution of the Lok Sabha, post the [[Indian general elections, 2014|2014 general elections]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/explained-why-the-citizenship-amendment-bill-is-dead-for-now-5582573/ | title=Explained: Why the Citizenship Amendment Bill is dead, for now | date=13 February 2019 | agency=Indian Express | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817130024/https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/explained-why-the-citizenship-amendment-bill-is-dead-for-now-5582573/ | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The 2016 bill had various provisions reportedly regressive to the provisions in the 2014 bill.<ref name=\"scroll\">{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/article/906205/this-is-a-black-day-activists-criticise-transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha | title=\u2018This is a black day\u2019: Activists criticise Transgender Persons Bill passed in Lok Sabha | date=19 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Lalwani, Vijayta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103231/https://scroll.in/article/906205/this-is-a-black-day-activists-criticise-transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jyotiratnam\" /> The bill was met with criticism and protests from Indian transgender persons and was referred to the standing committee, which submitted its report in July 2018.<ref name=\"jyotiratnam\" /> The Lok Sabha tabled and passed a newer version of the bill with twenty-seven amendments on 17 December 2018.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ptinews.com/news/10250267_Lok-Sabha-passes-Transgender-bill.html | title=Lok Sabha passes Transgender bill | date=17 December 2018 | agency=PRI | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092137/http://ptinews.com/news/10250267_Lok-Sabha-passes-Transgender-bill.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bittuh1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-transgender-persons-bill-misses-key-demands-of-the-community/story-0c6VV1GvYuV4xqYL06zw8N.html | title=The Transgender Persons Bill misses key demands of the community | date=15 June 2019 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kondaiah, Karthik Bittu | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817053704/https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-transgender-persons-bill-misses-key-demands-of-the-community/story-0c6VV1GvYuV4xqYL06zw8N.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was once again met with severe criticism and protests pan-India, as it overlooked the recommendations made by the standing committee and suggestions offered by transgender persons.<ref name=\"revised\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/colleges-join-hands-to-protest-against-transgender-bill-2018/article25844976.ece | title=Colleges join hands to protest against Transgender Bill 2018 | date=28 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Karangutkar, Suyash | location=Mumbai}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/rights-revised/article25783926.ece | title=Rights, revised: on the Transgender Persons Bill, 2018 | date=20 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> However, the 2018 bill stood lapsed.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-rights-bill-to-be-reintroduced/article27474400.ece | title=Transgender rights Bill to be reintroduced | date=5 June 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the constitution of the Lok Sabha, post the 2019 general elections, the bill was reintroduced on 19 July 2019 by the Minister of Social Justice and Empowerment, [[Thawar Chand Gehlot]].<ref name=\"leaflet1\">{{cite news | url=https://theleaflet.in/transgender-bill-introduced-in-the-lok-sabha/ | title=Transgender Bill introduced in the Lok Sabha | date=24 July 2019 | agency=The Leaflet | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sirohi, Nishant | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092851/https://theleaflet.in/transgender-bill-introduced-in-the-lok-sabha/ | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Before this the bill had been approved by the [[Cabinet of India|union cabinet]] on 10 July 2019.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/cabinet-approves-transgender-bill/article28355950.ece | title=Cabinet approves transgender bill | work=The Hindu Business Line | date=10 July 2019 | agency=Press Trust of India | accessdate=18 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311161745/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/cabinet-approves-transgender-bill/article28355950.ece | archive-date=11 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was passed by a voice vote in the Lok Sabha on 5 August 2019, amidst commotion in the house following the revocation of the state of Jammu and Kashmir's special status by the Parliament on the same day.<ref name=\"passedaugust\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-bill-passed-in-lok-sabha/article28822000.ece | title=Transgender Persons bill passed in Lok Sabha | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=PTI | location=New Delhi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/congress-opposition-parties-protest-in-lok-sabha-seek-presence-of-prime-minister-on-kashmir-decisions/articleshow/70536012.cms | title=Congress opposition parties protest in Lok Sabha seek presence of Prime Minister on Kashmir decision | date=5 August 2019 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808023548/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/congress-opposition-parties-protest-in-lok-sabha-seek-presence-of-prime-minister-on-kashmir-decisions/articleshow/70536012.cms | archive-date=8 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The bill was introduced in the Rajya Sabha by Thawarchand Gehlot on 20 November 2019, upon which it was passed without any amendments on 26 November 2019 following a motion to refer it to a [[Select_committee#India|select committee]] that failed by 77 noes against 55 ayes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/parliament-passes-bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders/article30087790.ece |title=Parliament passes Bill to protect rights of transgenders |work=26 November 2019 |access-date=17 April 2020 |publisher=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130183741/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/parliament-passes-bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders/article30087790.ece |archive-date=30 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name =\"jaya2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/amid-opposition-trans-community-rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-bill-112971 |title=Amid opposition from trans community, Rajya Sabha passes Transgender Persons Bill |date=26 November 2019 |work=The News Minute |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414175331/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/amid-opposition-trans-community-rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-bill-112971 |archive-date=14 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/rajya-sabha-passes-criticised-transgender-rights-bill |title=Rajya Sabha Passes Controversial Transgender Rights Bill |date=26 November 2019 |work=The Wire |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128190253/https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/rajya-sabha-passes-criticised-transgender-rights-bill |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The bill received presidential assent on 5 December 2019, following which the Ministry of Law and Justice notified it in the ''Gazette of India'' as Act No. 40 of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf |title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019 [No. 40 of 2019] |date=5 December 2019 |website=socialjustice.nic.in |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412014303/http://socialjustice.nic.in/writereaddata/UploadFile/TG%20bill%20gazette.pdf |archive-date=12 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name= \"despite\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/despite-massive-protests-trans-bill-gets-president-s-assent-becomes-law-113643 |title=Despite massive protests, Trans Bill gets President\u2019s assent, becomes law |date=7 December 2019 |work=The News Minute |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304050316/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/despite-massive-protests-trans-bill-gets-president-s-assent-becomes-law-113643 |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The act came into effect from 10 January 2020 onwards vide a notification in the ''Gazette'' on the same day by the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf |title=Notification, Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment |date=10 January 2020 |website=egazette.nic.in |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111034026/http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2020/215301.pdf |archive-date=11 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Nath |first=Damini |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-act-comes-into-effect/article30545336.ece |title=Transgender Persons Act comes into effect |date=11 January 2020 |work=The Hindu |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229091631/https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/transgender-persons-act-comes-into-effect/article30545336.ece |archive-date=29 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Statutory provisions==\nThe 2018 bill had criminalised begging \u2014 which transgender persons in India, such as the hijras and jogtas, engage in as a ritual-custom while some rely on it for livelihood \u2014 apart from mandating applications made to the [[District magistrate (India)|district magistrate]] to be screened through a district screening committee for issuance of transgender person certificates.<ref name =\"indiatoday2017\"/><ref name=\"billreaction1\"/> The screening committee was to be composed of five people including a chief medical officer, district social welfare officer, psychologist/psychiatrist, and a representative of the transgender persons<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.prsindia.org/billtrack/transgender-persons-protection-rights-bill-2016 | title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2016 | publisher=PRS Legislative Research | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=PRS India | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819031027/http://www.prsindia.org/billtrack/transgender-persons-protection-rights-bill-2016 | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/against-the-mandate-for-inclusion/article25791080.ece | title=Against the mandate for inclusion: the Transgender Persons Bill 2018 | date=21 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=19 August 2019 | author=Banerjie, Ajita}}</ref> The 2018 bill had also not provided for mandatory reservations for transgender persons and mandated lower punishment for crimes against transgender persons, as compared to punishment for crimes against cisgender persons under the [[Indian Penal Code]].<ref name =\"jyotiratnam\"/><ref name=\"bittuh1\"/> It also ensured a family-life for transgender children, by prohibiting their separation from their family, without taking into account harassment and discrimination they may face within their family as a result of which they may choose to be separated and reside with transgender persons.<ref name = \"herald\"/><ref name = \"economic\"/> A transgender child, as per the provisions, could be separated from their family only by a court order.<ref name = \"revised\"/> The 2018 bill provided for undergoing sex reassignment surgery as a mandatory pre-requirement to be identified as male or female.<ref name =\"frontline\">{{Cite news |url=https://frontline.thehindu.com/dispatches/article25957990.ece |title=Stiff opposition to transgender persons Bill |last=Venkatesan |first=V. |date=10 January 2019 |work=Frontline |access-date=20 September 2019 |last2=Kaur |first2=Tanveer}}</ref> The 2019 act does away only with few of the criticised provisions of the 2018 bill, such as the district screening committee and the criminalisation of begging.<ref name=\"reuters1\"/>\n\nThe statutory provisions of the 2019 act prohibit discrimination against transgender persons.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-lgbt-lawmaking/india-introduces-new-trans-rights-bill-in-parliament-after-backlash-idUSKCN1UE28S | title=India introduces new trans rights bill in parliament after backlash | date=19 July 2019 | agency=Reuters | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Banerji, Annie | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074604/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-lgbt-lawmaking/india-introduces-new-trans-rights-bill-in-parliament-after-backlash-idUSKCN1UE28S | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Similar to the 2018 bill, the 2019 act includes [[intersex|intersex persons]], hijras, jogtas, and [[kinnar]]s within its definition of transgender persons,<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/govt-making-rules-for-us-without-us-transgenders/article29104679.ece | title=Govt. making rules for us without us: transgenders | date=16 August 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Aggarwal, Aarushi | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815231759/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/govt-making-rules-for-us-without-us-transgenders/article29104679.ece | archive-date=15 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> though it does not define terms such as trans-man, trans-woman, and [[genderqueer]].<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref name=\"tribune1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/comment/bringing-transgenders-into-mainstream/807918.html |title=Bringing transgenders into mainstream |last=Quraishi |first=S. Y. |date=26 July 2019 |work=The Tribune |accessdate=17 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817104013/https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/comment/bringing-transgenders-into-mainstream/807918.html |archive-date=17 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Both, the 2019 act as well as the 2018 bill, describe a transgender person as someone whose gender does not match with the gender assigned to them at birth.<ref name =\"frontline\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/The%20Transgender%20Persons%20%28Protection%20of%20Rights%29%20Bill%2C%202019%20Bill%20Text.pdf |title=The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill (No. 169), 2019 |work=PRS Legislative Research |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nUnder the provisions of the 2019 act, a transgender person can apply to the district magistrate for a transgender person certificate which will give them the right to change the name on their birth certificate and have all documents updated accordingly.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-rights-bill-a-stunted-understanding-of-gender-and-equality | title=Transgender Rights Bill: A Stunted Understanding of Gender and Equality | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The Wire | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gandhi, and Ghia | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802165656/https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-rights-bill-a-stunted-understanding-of-gender-and-equality | archive-date=2 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> However, similar to the 2018 bill provisions, a transgender person can be identified as male or female only after applying for a revised certificate to the district magistrate, post sex reassignment surgery.<ref name=\"newsminute1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-transgender-persons-bill-2018-public-health-nightmare-community-94206 | title=Why Transgender Persons Bill 2018 is a healthcare nightmare for the community | date=30 December 2018 | agency=The News Minute | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Karpagam, Sylvia | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074604/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/why-transgender-persons-bill-2018-public-health-nightmare-community-94206 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 act also protects transgender children and provides for states and institutions to come up with adequate policies for the welfare of transgender persons.<ref name=\"dh\">{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders-passed-in-ls-752193.html | title=Bill to protect rights of transgenders passed in LS | date=5 August 2019 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kumar, Prakash | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817095008/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/bill-to-protect-rights-of-transgenders-passed-in-ls-752193.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name = \"economic\">{{cite news | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/transgender-rights-bill-introduced-in-lok-sabha-may-be-taken-up-next-week/articleshow/70301454.cms | title=Transgender Rights Bill introduced in Lok Sabha, may be taken up next week | date=20 July 2019 | agency=Economic Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Sharma, Nidhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817094010/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/transgender-rights-bill-introduced-in-lok-sabha-may-be-taken-up-next-week/articleshow/70301454.cms | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Similar to the provisions of the 2018 bill, under the provisions of the 2019 act a transgender child can be separated from their family by a court order.<ref name = \"revised\"/> However, unlike the Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014 neither the 2018 bill nor the 2019 act provide for mandatory reservations for transgender persons in educational institutions and jobs.<ref name=\"leaflet1\"/> The 2014 bill had provided for two per-cent reservations in educational institutions and public employment.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/a-law-that-defeats-its-purpose/article25854190.ece | title=A law that defeats its purpose | date=29 December 2018 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Kothari, Jayna}}</ref> Similar to the 2018 bill, the 2019 act provides for punishment for crimes against transgender persons, which stands as an imprisonment for a term not less than six months but which may extend to two years and a fine.<ref name =\"jyotiratnam\"/><ref name =\"tribune1\"/> The 2019 act, as well as the 2018 bill, also provide for the constitution of a National Council for Transgender Persons.<ref name = \"passedaugust\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-lok-sabha-passes-bill-to-prohibit-discrimination-against-transgenders-2779179 | title=Lok Sabha passes bill to prohibit discrimination against transgenders | date=5 August 2019 | agency=DNA | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=ANI | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806145618/https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-lok-sabha-passes-bill-to-prohibit-discrimination-against-transgenders-2779179 | archive-date=6 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and reactions==\n[[File:Protest against Transgender Bill in Mumbai, India.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Protests against the 2018 bill in [[Mumbai]], in December 2018]]\nThe 2018 bill passed by the Lok Sabha was widely criticised by transgender persons, activists, students, and lawyers.<ref name=\"gautamh1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-rajya-sabha-must-amend-the-transgender-persons-bill/story-WEyPFztPVABpfaQyDYBt5I.html | title=The Rajya Sabha must amend the Transgender Persons Bill | date=5 January 2019 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Bhatia, Gautam | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817073521/https://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/the-rajya-sabha-must-amend-the-transgender-persons-bill/story-WEyPFztPVABpfaQyDYBt5I.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Transgender persons protested in various cities in India calling the provisions regressive and in violation of the Supreme Court judgment in 2014.<ref name=\"bittuh1\"/><ref name=\"jyotiratnam\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/transgender-bill-criminalises-community-say-activists-seek-its-overhaul/story-U6hfkKpilq6bxsDAd2WvJI.html | title=Transgender bill criminalises community, say activists; seek its overhaul | date=19 December 2018 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Jyoti, and Ratnam | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817072656/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/transgender-bill-criminalises-community-say-activists-seek-its-overhaul/story-U6hfkKpilq6bxsDAd2WvJI.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The criminalisation of begging under the 2018 bill was to affect transgender persons in India, such as hijras and jogtas, who engage in begging as a ritual-custom while some rely on it for livelihood.<ref name =\"indiatoday2017\">{{cite news | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lgbtq-community-protests-against-transgender-persons-bill-1110328-2017-12-17 | title=LGBTQ community protests against Transgender Persons Bill | date=17 December 2017 | agency=India Today | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Hasan, Ilma | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817092306/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lgbtq-community-protests-against-transgender-persons-bill-1110328-2017-12-17 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"billreaction1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/trans-activists-up-the-ante-to-challenge-bill/article25945066.ece | title=Trans activists up the ante, to challenge Bill | date=9 January 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Ravi, Sidharth | location=New Delhi}}</ref> It was alleged by critics that the provision of the district screening committee left gaps for incompetence and prejudice.<ref name =\"herald\">{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/opinion/second-edit/transgender-bill-remove-709703.html | title=Transgender Bill: remove drawbacks | date=24 December 2018 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030729/https://www.deccanherald.com/opinion/second-edit/transgender-bill-remove-709703.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' reported that even if the provision of a district screening committee existed to prevent imposters from seeking benefits of government welfare schemes, such an arrangement cannot be made at the expense of transgender persons' right to self-determination.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/editorials/transgender-rights-should-not-depend-on-a-screening/story-c1oqqLOTEzSAfyBoV0fWWN.html | title=Transgender rights should not depend on a screening | date=19 February 2018 | agency=Hindustan Times | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030729/https://www.hindustantimes.com/editorials/transgender-rights-should-not-depend-on-a-screening/story-c1oqqLOTEzSAfyBoV0fWWN.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The definition of transgender persons under the 2018 bill, retained by the 2019 act, was reported by ''[[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]]'' to be at variance with international expert understanding of the term.<ref name =\"frontline\"/>\n\nThe 2018 bill and 2019 act have been met with protests by transgender persons.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/dec/22/1k-trans-people-from-pondy-tn-protest-against-new-law-1914889.html | title=Over 1,000 transgenders from Pondicherry, Tamil Nadu protest against new law | date=22 December 2018 | agency=New Indian Express | accessdate=19 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030732/http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2018/dec/22/1k-trans-people-from-pondy-tn-protest-against-new-law-1914889.html | archive-date=19 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Their passing by the parliament has been referred to some transgender persons as \"black day\" and \"gender justice murder day\".<ref name= \"despite\"/><ref name = \"scroll\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/aug/08/transgender-persons-bill-evokes-mixed-responses-2015785.html | title=Transgender Persons Bill evokes mixed responses | date=8 August 2019 | agency=The New Indian Express | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Gowda, Varsha | location=Bengaluru | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103657/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bengaluru/2019/aug/08/transgender-persons-bill-evokes-mixed-responses-2015785.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Yet others described them as \"draconian and discriminatory\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/bill-will-deprive-us-of-right-to-live-with-dignity-say-transgender-activists/article25837198.ece |title=Bill will deprive us of right to live with dignity, say transgender activists |last=Karangutkar |first=Suyash |date=27 December 2018 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref> After the 2018 bill was passed by the Lok Sabha in December 2018, members of the opposition in Rajya Sabha had stated they will not let the bill pass in its present form in Rajya Sabha.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://scroll.in/latest/907430/transgender-persons-bill-opposition-mps-in-rajya-sabha-promise-not-to-pass-draft-law | title=Transgender Persons Bill: Opposition MPs in Rajya Sabha promise not to pass draft law | date=28 December 2018 | agency=Scroll | accessdate=17 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817103316/https://scroll.in/latest/907430/transgender-persons-bill-opposition-mps-in-rajya-sabha-promise-not-to-pass-draft-law | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Protestors alleged the 2018 bill to be institutionalising violence and claimed neglect of recommendations made by the standing committee and transgender persons.<ref name=\"hubbali\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/withdraw-transgenders-bill-table-it-again-with-changes/article25875808.ece |title=\u2018Withdraw Transgenders Bill, table it again with changes\u2019  |date=1 January 2019 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 September 2019}}</ref> Transgender persons called for applications to the district magistrate for issuance of transgender certificates, lesser punishment for crimes against transgender persons, and absence of provisions on mandatory reservations for transgender persons regressive to the judicial mandate of the Supreme Court in 2014 in ''NALSA v. UOI'', thereby violating right to equality and other fundamental rights of transgender persons.<ref name=\"hubbali\"/><ref name=\"newsminute2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/trans-bill-2019-passed-lok-sabha-why-trans-community-india-rejecting-it-106695 | title=Trans Bill 2019 passed in Lok Sabha: Why the trans community in India is rejecting it | date=5 August 2019 | agency=The News Minute | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Dharmadhikari, Sanyukta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817074728/https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/trans-bill-2019-passed-lok-sabha-why-trans-community-india-rejecting-it-106695 | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nIn the run-up to the 2019 general elections to the Lok Sabha, Indian National Congress had promised in its electoral manifesto to withdraw the 2018 bill and introduce a new one, in consultation with members of the queer community.<ref name = \"manifesto\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestatesman.com/elections-2019/congress-releases-poll-manifesto-promises-jobs-benefits-farmers-niti-aayog-1502742568.html | title=Congress manifesto promises 34 lakh jobs, farmer welfare, says will scrap NITI Aayog | date=2 April 2019 | agency=The Statesman | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=SNS Web | location=New Delhi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817134723/https://www.thestatesman.com/elections-2019/congress-releases-poll-manifesto-promises-jobs-benefits-farmers-niti-aayog-1502742568.html | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The Communist Party of India (Marxist) had supported the passing of the 2014 bill in its electoral manifesto.<ref name = \"manifesto\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/elections/lok-sabha-2019/the-invisible-third-gender-voters/article26764806.ece | title=The invisible \u2018third gender\u2019 voters | date=8 April 2019 | agency=The Hindu | accessdate=17 August 2019 | author=Rosario, Kennith | location=Mumbai}}</ref> In April 2019, transgender rights activist, [[Laxmi Narayan Tripathi]], met the then [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] National General Secretary, [[Ram Madhav]], seeking that the party would introduce a revised bill if it comes back to power.<ref name=\"laxmi\">{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/transgender-activist-meets-ram-madhav-seeks-revised-bill-if-bjp-is-returned-to-power/articleshow/68745108.cms | title=Transgender activist meets Ram Madhav, seeks revised bill if BJP is returned to power | work=Times of India | date=5 April 2019 | accessdate=18 April 2020 | author=Pandit, Ambika | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920204451/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/transgender-activist-meets-ram-madhav-seeks-revised-bill-if-bjp-is-returned-to-power/articleshow/68745108.cms | archive-date=20 September 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Madhav ensured that the bill would address the concerns of the transgender community.<ref name=\"laxmi\"/> Soon after news reported that the 2019 bill was approved by the union cabinet, transgender rights activists called for a press conference in Delhi to address the issue.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-bill-cabinet-lok-sabha-activists | title=Trans Activists Demand Release of Full Text of Cabinet-Approved Transgender Bill | work=The Wire | date=17 July 2019 | accessdate=18 April 2020 | author=Sharma, Raghavi | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817091259/https://thewire.in/lgbtqia/transgender-bill-cabinet-lok-sabha-activists | archive-date=17 August 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> On 24 November 2019, two days before the bill was passed by the parliament, protests were staged by the queer community in New Delhi and [[Bengaluru]] as part of the [[Delhi Queer Pride Parade|Delhi queer pride parade]] and the [[Bengaluru Namma Pride March]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/namma-pride-march-rainbow-spreads-cheer-but-with-a-dash-of-black/articleshow/72216384.cms | title=Namma Pride March: Rainbow spread cheer, but with a dash of black | date=25 November 2019 | agency=Times of India | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Iyer, Swathy R | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129065826/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/namma-pride-march-rainbow-spreads-cheer-but-with-a-dash-of-black/articleshow/72216384.cms | archive-date=29 November 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/delhi-marched-against-trans-bill-2019-on-pride-day-779641.html | title=Delhi marched against Trans Bill 2019 on Pride Day | date=25 November 2019 | agency=Deccan Herald | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Banerjee, Rohini | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123135718/https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/delhi-marched-against-trans-bill-2019-on-pride-day-779641.html | archive-date=23 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jaya\">{{Cite news |last=Pathak |first=Sushmita |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/12/04/784398783/india-just-passed-a-trans-rights-bill-why-are-trans-activists-protesting-it |title=India Just Passed A Trans Rights Bill. Why Are Trans Activists Protesting It? |date=4 December 2019 |work=National Public Radio |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303211742/https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/12/04/784398783/india-just-passed-a-trans-rights-bill-why-are-trans-activists-protesting-it |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The legislation also drew criticism from the [[All India Mahila Congress]] and opposition from parliamentarians including [[Jaya Bachchan]] and [[Sasmit Patra]], while [[Derek O'Brien (politician)|Derek O\u2019Brien]] and Tiruchi Siva also expressed their concerns before the house.<ref name=\"jaya2\"/><ref name=\"jaya\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/a-bill-meant-to-protect-indias-transgender-community-instead-leaves-them-angry-and-aggrieved/2019/11/29/6c2c7b7e-116b-11ea-924c-b34d09bbc948_story.html | title=A bill meant to protect India\u2019s transgender community instead leaves them angry and aggrieved | date=30 November 2019 | agency=The Washington Post | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Masih, Niha | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302034520/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia-pacific/a-bill-meant-to-protect-indias-transgender-community-instead-leaves-them-angry-and-aggrieved/2019/11/29/6c2c7b7e-116b-11ea-924c-b34d09bbc948_story.html | archive-date=2 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> After the legislation was passed by the parliament, transgender persons and activists protested against the legislation, organised meetings to address the situation, and urged the president not to sign and assent to the bill.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/other/protests-held-in-dadar-against-transgender-persons-bill-2019/articleshow/72309119.cms | title=Protests held in Dadar against Transgender Persons Bill 2019 | work=Mumbai Mirror | date=1 December 2019 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201051151/https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/other/protests-held-in-dadar-against-transgender-persons-bill-2019/articleshow/72309119.cms | archive-date=1 December 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"jaya\"/> <ref>{{Cite news |last=Khan |first=Fatima |url=https://theprint.in/india/murder-of-gender-justice-activists-urge-president-kovind-not-to-sign-transgender-bill/327360/ |title=\u2018Murder of gender justice\u2019 \u2014 activists urge President Kovind not to sign transgender bill |date=27 November 2019 |work=The Print |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201121026/https://theprint.in/india/murder-of-gender-justice-activists-urge-president-kovind-not-to-sign-transgender-bill/327360/ |archive-date=1 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> There were also protests by the queer community against the act as part of the [[Queer Azaadi Mumbai|Mumbai pride parade]], in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/take-back-trans-act-mumbai-trans-community/1726557 | title=Take back Trans Act: Mumbai Trans community | work=Outlook | date=5 February 2020 | agency=IANS | accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/mumbai-pride-2020-thousands-stand-in-solidarity-with-queer-muslims-amid-caa-nrc-chaos-urge-govt-to-amend-draconian-transgender-act-7991111.html | title=Mumbai Pride 2020: Thousands stand in solidarity with queer Muslims amid CAA-NRC chaos, urge govt to amend 'draconian' Transgender Act | work=Firstpost | date=25 February 2020 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Manral, Avnisha | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315122340/https://www.firstpost.com/india/mumbai-pride-2020-thousands-stand-in-solidarity-with-queer-muslims-amid-caa-nrc-chaos-urge-govt-to-amend-draconian-transgender-act-7991111.html | archive-date=15 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe legislation has been criticised by [[Human Rights Watch]] and the [[International Commission of Jurists]].<ref name=\"jurists\">{{Cite news |last=Sharma |first=Neetu Chandra |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-protection-of-rights-bill-2019-11574774522034.html |title=Rajya Sabha passes Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Bill, 2019 |date=26 November 2019 |work=Live Mint |access-date=17 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128004011/https://www.livemint.com/news/india/rajya-sabha-passes-transgender-persons-protection-of-rights-bill-2019-11574774522034.html |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"hrw\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/07/23/india-transgender-bill-raises-rights-concerns | title=India: Transgender Bill Raises Rights Concerns | date=23 July 2019 | agency=Human Rights Watch | accessdate=17 August 2019 | location=New York | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730050854/https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/07/23/india-transgender-bill-raises-rights-concerns | archive-date=30 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> On 27 January 2020, the Supreme Court issued a notice to the central government in a petition filed by advocate and transgender rights activist, Swati Bidhan Baruah, challenging the constitutionality of the 2019 legislation.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act/story-HfBrPZBTFmusm9theecWoL.html | title=Supreme Court notice to Centre on plea against transgender act | work=Hindustan Times | date=28 January 2020 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129045020/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act/story-HfBrPZBTFmusm9theecWoL.html | archive-date=29 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/supreme-court-notice-to-centre-on-plea-against-transgender-act-2019-798774.html | title=Supreme Court notice to Centre on plea against Transgender Act, 2019| work=Deccan Herald | date=27 January 2020 | agency=Tripathi, Ashish | accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[LGBT rights in India]]\n*[[Human rights in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|The Transgender Persons (Protection of Rights) Act, 2019}}\n* [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Expert_Committee_Report_%282014%29_1.pdf   Report of the Expert Committee on Issues Relating to Transgender Persons (27 January 2014)]\n* [http://www.prsindia.org/sites/default/files/bill_files/Transgender_Bill%2C_2015_-_PMB_passed_in_RS_2.pdf   The Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014]\n\n{{Indian legislation}}\n{{LGBT in India}}\n{{Transgender topics}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT rights in India]]\n[[Category:Modi administration]]\n[[Category:Transgender law]]\n[[Category:2019 in Indian law]]\n", "name_user": "Bilorv", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transgender_Persons_(Protection_of_Rights)_Act,_2019"}
